# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: binary-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] A **binary file** is a computer file that is not a text file.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] The term "binary file" is often used as a term meaning "non-text file".
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Many binary file formats contain parts that can be interpreted as text; for example, some computer document files containing formatted text, such as older Microsoft Word document files, contain the text of the document but also contain formatting information in binary form.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] All modern computers store information in the form of bits (binary digits), using binary code.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] For this reason, all data stored on a computer is, in some sense, "binary".
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] However, one particularly useful and ubiquitous type of data stored on a computer is one in which the bits represent text, by way of a character encoding.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Those files are called "text files" and files which are not like that are referred to as "binary files", as a sort of retronym or hypernym.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] These mixed binary-and-text file are usually regarded as "binary", because an application that can only process text will not know what to do with them.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] For example, in a binary file, the number 250 could be encoded in bits as the sequence 11111010.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] It could also be encoded in a text file (for example, a programming language source file) as the digits 2, 5, 0; which would in turn be encoded by the bits in the text file as (for example, using UTF-8) 00110010, 00110101, 00110000.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Binary files are usually thought of as being a sequence of bytes, which means the binary digits (bits) are grouped in eights.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Binary files typically contain bytes that are intended to be interpreted as something other than text characters.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Compiled computer programs are typical examples; indeed, compiled applications are sometimes referred to, particularly by programmers, as **binaries**.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] But binary files can also mean that they contain images, sounds, compressed versions of other files, etc. – in short, any type of file content whatsoever.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Some binary files contain headers, blocks of metadata used by a computer program to interpret the data in the file.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] The header often contains a signature or *magic* number which can identify the format.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] For example, a GIF file can contain multiple images, and headers are used to identify and describe each block of image data.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] The leading bytes of the header would contain text like `GIF87a` or `GIF89a` that can identify the binary as a GIF file.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] If a binary file does not contain any headers, it may be called a **flat binary file**.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] A text file may consist partly or entirely of encoded binary information.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] When sending binary files over the network they may be encoded so that they use only printable characters.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] This is often necessary due to the limitations of network protocols used for internet browsing and e-mail communication.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Also, files containing public-key and private-key information for use in systems employing asymmetric cryptography (such as website certificates) may also be stored with the binary information encoded in printable characters.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] To send binary files through certain systems (such as email) that do not allow all data values, they are often translated into a plain text representation (using, for example, Base64).
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Encoding the data has the disadvantage of increasing the file size during the transfer (for example, using Base64 will increase the file's size by approximately 30%), as well as requiring translation back into binary after receipt.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] The increased size may be countered by lower-level link compression, as the resulting text data will have about as much less entropy as it has increased size, so the actual data transferred in this scenario would likely be very close to the size of the original binary data.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] See Binary-to-text encoding for more on this subject.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] In Unix-like systems, the C and C++ standard libraries on those systems also allow the programmer to specify whether a file is expected to be text or binary, but the libraries can and do ignore that parameter, as the end-of-line sequence in Unix-like systems is just the C/C++ end-of-line character.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] A hex editor or viewer may be used to view file data as a sequence of hexadecimal (or decimal, binary or ASCII character) values for corresponding bytes of a binary file.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] If a binary file is opened in a text editor, each group of eight bits will typically be translated as a single character, and the user will see a (probably unintelligible) display of textual characters.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] If the file is opened in some other application, that application will have its own use for each byte: maybe the application will treat each byte as a number and output a stream of numbers between 0 and 255—or maybe interpret the numbers in the bytes as colors and display the corresponding picture.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Other type of viewers (called 'word extractors') simply replace the unprintable characters with spaces revealing only the human-readable text.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] This type of view is useful for a quick inspection of a binary file in order to find passwords in games, find hidden text in non-text files and recover corrupted documents.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] It can even be used to inspect suspicious files (software) for unwanted effects.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] For example, the user would see any URL/email to which the suspected software may attempt to connect in order to upload unapproved data (to steal).
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] If the file is itself treated as an executable and run, then the operating system will attempt to interpret the file as a series of instructions in its machine language.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Standards are very important to binary files.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] For example, a binary file interpreted by the ASCII character set will result in text being displayed.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] A custom application can interpret the file differently: a byte may be a sound, or a pixel, or even an entire word.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Binary itself is meaningless, until such time as an executed algorithm defines what should be done with each bit, byte, word or block.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Thus, just examining the binary and attempting to match it against known formats can lead to the wrong conclusion as to what it actually represents.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] This fact can be used in steganography, where an algorithm interprets a binary data file differently to reveal hidden content.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Without the algorithm, it is impossible to tell that hidden content exists.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Two files that are binary compatible will have the same sequence of zeros and ones in the data portion of the file.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] The file header, however, may be different.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] The term is used most commonly to state that data files produced by one application are exactly the same as data files produced by another application.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] For example, some software companies produce applications for Windows and the Macintosh that are binary compatible, which means that a file produced in a Windows environment is interchangeable with a file produced on a Macintosh.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] This avoids many of the conversion problems caused by importing and exporting data.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] One possible binary compatibility issue between different computers is the endianness of the computer.
[src:binary-analysis/binary-file] Some computers store the bytes in a file in a different order.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] In computer science, a **control-flow graph** (**CFG**) is a representation, using graph notation, of all paths that might be traversed through a function during its execution, or control flow.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The control-flow graph was conceived by Frances E.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Prosser used boolean connectivity matrices for flow analysis before.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The CFG is essential to many compiler optimizations and static-analysis tools.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A control flow graph is the directed graph of the basic blocks of the function (the nodes of the graph) and the control flow between them (the edges of the graph).
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The exact details vary between representations.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Typically, a basic block consists of a straight-line sequence of instructions or statements.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Only the last instruction or statement in each block can perform control flow, and control flow can only be directed to the first instruction or statement in a block.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] In most CFG representations, there are two specially designated blocks: the *entry block*, through which control enters into the function, and the *exit block*, through which all control exits the function (typically by returning).
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Some representations permit multiple exit blocks, especially if there are different kinds of exit, or permit the exit block to be omitted if it is not reachable .
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] If there is a control-flow edge from block A to block B, then A is called a *predecessor* of B, and B is called a *successor* of A.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The nested structure of the source program makes it a little hard to see the basic blocks.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] As an alternative representation that makes the blocks more obvious, we can flatten that structure into a sequence of labeled blocks.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] To make the control flow explicit, we will require each block to end in either `goto`, an `if`/`else` of `goto`s, or `return` (only in the exit block).
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] This is a source-level representation of the CFG.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The basic blocks consist of sequences of C statements taken directly from the source program.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Only the structured control flow has been eliminated.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] This style of statement-level CFG representation is not commonly used, and it is shown here only for illustrative purposes.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Not all programs can be easily represented this way, even in C.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Notice how the local variable declaration has been raised to the top of function, and its initialization in `block1` has been turned into an assignment.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] This would cause difficulties for scope-driven features such as shadowing and variable-length arrays.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Statements would also need to be significantly rewritten to deal with expression-level control flow, such as is introduced by the `&&`, `||`, and `? :` operators.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Most practical CFG representations use something other than complete source statements as the components of their basic blocks.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] For example, compiler frameworks such as LLVM use a CFG in which basic blocks consist of abstract static single-assignment instructions as their primary IR.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Notice how the block structure is the same in the source-level and the LLVM CFGs.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] In both representations, the functions have the same basic semantics, performing the same sequence of operations and control flow.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Only the representation of the individual operations is different.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A very explicit control flow graph can be obtained from a source function by placing each statement into its own basic block.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] If the statement is not a control-flow statement, a "fall-through" jump to the block for the next statement is added to the block.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Unfortunately, this tends to create a large number of unnecessary basic blocks and fall-through jumps, which makes subsequent analysis more cumbersome and expensive.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] It is usually desirable that successive statements be placed in the same basic block whenever possible.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] However, this contraction-based algorithm is of little practical importance except as a visualization aid for understanding CFG construction because of the expense of building the initial form.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] In typical implementations, the CFG is built directly from the program in a way that minimizes unnecessary blocks by construction, such as by scanning the program for necessary boundaries between basic blocks.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Reachability is a graph property useful in optimization.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] If a block cannot be reached by any path from the entry block, then it cannot possibly be executed, in which case it is called unreachable code.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Unreachable code can usually be removed from the control flow graph without any negative consequences.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] If the exit block cannot be reached by any path from the entry block, then control flow cannot leave the graph normally.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] This indicates the presence of either an infinite loop or, in representations that directly support these features, an abnormal exit or termination of the program.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The exit block being reachable by some path does not mean that the program will necessarily reach it, and it is impossible to prove that it will be reached in a general graph; see Halting problem.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Optimization can reveal unreachable code and infinite loops that were not apparent in the original program.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] In this form, the loop in this function is not an infinite loop because there is a path which leaves the loop: if `%3` is false, the program will branch to `block3` and return.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] However, a numerical analysis can prove that the product of any number and 2 will be even, which means that `%2` is always zero and `%3` can never be false.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] There is now an infinite loop in the control flow graph, and the exit block can no longer be reached.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Note that this optimization did not change the behavior of the program: it was always true that the loop would never exit.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] All that has changed is that the control flow graph is more accurately reflecting that truth.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A block M *dominates* a block N if every path from the entry that reaches block N also has to visit block M.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] M is said to *properly dominate* N if M dominates N and they are different blocks.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Furthermore, an individual statement or instruction X is said to properly dominate a statement or instruction Y if the block containing X dominates the block containing Y and, if those are the same block, X strictly precedes Y in the block.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] It is said that a block M *immediately dominates* block N if M dominates N, and there is no intervening block P such that M dominates P and P dominates N.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] In other words, M is the last dominator on all paths from entry to N.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Every reachable block has a unique immediate dominator except for the entry block, which has none.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The *dominator tree* is a directed graph representing the dominance relationships in the function.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The nodes of the graph are the reachable basic blocks of the function, and there is an edge from block M to block N if M is an immediate dominator of N.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Since each non-entry reachable block has a unique immediate dominator, this is a tree rooted at the entry block.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The dominator tree can be calculated efficiently using Lengauer–Tarjan's algorithm.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] In the reverse direction, block M *post-dominates* block N if every path from N to the exit also has to visit block M.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] (This is sometimes written without a hyphen: M *postdominates* N.) The exit block post-dominates all blocks.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] M is said to *properly post-dominate* N if it post-dominates N and they are different blocks.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] M is an *immediate post-dominator* of N if it post-dominates N and there is no block P such that M post-dominates P and P post-dominates N.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Every block from which the exit block is reachable has a unique immediate post-dominator except for the exit block, which has none.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] This gives rise to a *post-dominator tree*, rooted at the exit block, over the blocks from which the exit block is reachable.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The standard definition of dominance includes unreachable blocks, and the standard definition of post-dominance includes blocks from which the exit block cannot be reached.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] However, such blocks have unique properties under these relationships: an unreachable block is dominated by all blocks, and a block from which the exit cannot be reached is post-dominated by all blocks.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Most analyses relying on dominance or post-dominance will want to ignore them, and they are not included in dominator or post-dominator trees.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Some representations require the addition of *impossible edges* to prevent these blocks from existing, at least formally.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A *critical edge* is an edge which is neither the only edge leaving its source block, nor the only edge entering its destination block.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Some optimizations must *split* critical edges in order to insert instructions along the edge without affecting other paths through the program.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] An edge is split by creating a new block that contains only a jump to the destination block, then replacing the original branch destination with the new block.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A *retreating edge* is an edge for which there exists a simple path from the entry block to the source block of the edge (such as might be found by a depth-first traversal of the graph) which includes the destination block.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A retreating edge indicates the presence of a cycle in the control flow graph.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A retreating edge is called a *back edge* if the destination block is present on all possible paths to the source block, which is to say, if the destination block dominates the source block.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] An *abnormal edge* is an edge whose destination is unknown.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Exception handling constructs can produce them.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] These edges tend to inhibit optimization.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] An *impossible edge* (also known as a *fake edge*) is an edge which cannot actually be traversed during execution and is only added to the graph to preserve some useful property.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] For example, some representations require the addition of impossible edges to ensure that the exit block is always reachable and post-dominates all blocks.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A strongly-connected component (SCC) of a control flow graph is a set of basic blocks which are all reachable from one another.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The blocks that are part of a loop are always part of the same strongly-connected component.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A block that is not part of a cycle is always in a strongly-connected component by itself.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] In particular, the entry and exit blocks are always their own strongly-connected components.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The strongly-connected components of a CFG form a directed acyclic graph called the *SCC tree*, where component A has an edge to component B if any block in A has an edge to any block in B.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The SCC tree is isomorphic to the control flow graph if there are no cycles in the CFG; if there is a cycle, the SCC tree essentially collapses all blocks and edges in it into a single node.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] This can be useful for analyses that wish to treat all of the blocks in a cycle as equivalent.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] For example, when trying to find an object lifetime that covers a set of use-points as narrowly as possible, if one of those use-points is within a cyclic SCC, the lifetime must fully cover every block in that component.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A *loop header* (sometimes called the *entry point* of the loop) is a dominator that is the target of a loop-forming back edge.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The loop header dominates all blocks in the loop body.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A block may be a loop header for more than one loop.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A loop may have multiple entry points, in which case it has no "loop header".
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Suppose block M is a dominator with several incoming edges, some of them being back edges (so M is a loop header).
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] It is advantageous to several optimization passes to break M up into two blocks Mpre and Mloop.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The contents of M and back edges are moved to Mloop, the rest of the edges are moved to point into Mpre, and a new edge from Mpre to Mloop is inserted (so that Mpre is the immediate dominator of Mloop).
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] In the beginning, Mpre would be empty, but passes like loop-invariant code motion could populate it.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Mpre is called the *loop pre-header*, and Mloop would be the loop header.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] A control flow graph is called *reducible* if all its retreating edges are back edges.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The other edges in such a CFG are called *forward edges*.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The forward edges form a directed acyclic graph, and the back edges always lead to a basic block that control flow has already passed through.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Reducible CFGs generally have stronger static properties and can be more easily analyzed and optimized.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] For example, many loop optimizations are designed to work only on reducible CFGs.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Structured programming languages are often designed such that all CFGs they produce are reducible, and common structured programming statements such as IF, FOR, WHILE, BREAK, and CONTINUE reliably produce reducible graphs.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] To directly produce an irreducible graph, statements such as GOTO are needed that can jump to an arbitrary point in the program, although not all uses of GOTO produce irreducible CFGs.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Irreducible CFGs can also be produced by some compiler optimizations, such as jump threading.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Irreducible CFGs can be converted to reducible CFGs, but this often requires duplicating code or introducing new variables to the program.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The loop connectedness of a CFG is defined with respect to a given depth-first search tree (DFST) of the CFG.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] This DFST should be rooted at the start node and cover every node of the CFG.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] In this context, edges in the CFG which run from a node to one of its DFST ancestors (including itself) are called back edges.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] This does not necessarily coincide with the usual definition of a back edge because a DFST ancestor need not dominate the source node of the edge.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] The loop connectedness is the largest number of back edges found in any cycle-free path of the CFG.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] In a reducible CFG, the loop connectedness is independent of the DFST chosen.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] Loop connectedness has been used to reason about the time complexity of data-flow analysis.
[src:binary-analysis/control-flow-graph] While control-flow graphs represent the control flow of a single procedure, inter-procedural control-flow graphs represent the control flow of whole programs.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] In computing, the **Executable and Linkable Format** (**ELF**, formerly named **Extensible Linking Format**) is a common standard file format for executable files, object code, shared libraries, device drivers, and core dumps.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] First published in the specification for the application binary interface (ABI) of the Unix operating system version named System V Release 4 (SVR4), and later in the Tool Interface Standard, it was quickly accepted among different vendors of Unix systems.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] In 1999, it was chosen as the standard binary file format for Unix and Unix-like systems on x86 processors by the 86open project.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] By design, the ELF format is flexible, extensible, and cross-platform.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] For instance, it supports different endiannesses and address sizes so it does not exclude any particular CPU or instruction set architecture.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] This has allowed it to be adopted by many different operating systems on many different hardware platforms.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] Each ELF file is made up of one ELF header, followed by file data.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The segments contain information that is needed for run time execution of the file, while sections contain important data for linking and relocation.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] Any byte in the entire file can be owned by one section at most, and orphan bytes can occur which are unowned by any section.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The ELF header defines whether to use 32-bit or 64-bit addresses.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The header contains three fields that are affected by this setting and offset other fields that follow them.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The ELF header is 52 or 64 bytes long for 32-bit and 64-bit binaries, respectively.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The program header table tells the system how to create a process image.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] It is found at file offset e_phoff, and consists of e_phnum entries, each with size e_phentsize.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The layout is slightly different in 32-bit ELF vs 64-bit ELF, because the p_flags are in a different structure location for alignment reasons.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The ELF format has replaced older executable formats in various environments.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] Microsoft Windows also uses the ELF format, but only for its Windows Subsystem for Linux compatibility system.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] Some phones can run ELF files through the use of a patch that adds assembly code to the main firmware, which is a feature known as *ELFPack* in the underground modding culture.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The ELF file format is also used with the Atmel AVR (8-bit), AVR32 and with Texas Instruments MSP430 microcontroller architectures.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] Some implementations of Open Firmware can also load ELF files, most notably Apple's implementation used in almost all PowerPC machines the company produced.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The Linux Standard Base (LSB) supplements some of the above specifications for architectures in which it is specified.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] For example, that is the case for the System V ABI, AMD64 Supplement.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The format eventually chosen was ELF, specifically the Linux implementation of ELF, after it had turned out to be a *de facto* standard supported by all involved vendors and operating systems.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The group began email discussions in 1997 and first met together at the Santa Cruz Operation offices on August 22, 1997.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The steering committee was Marc Ewing, Dion Johnson, Evan Leibovitch, Bruce Perens, Andrew Roach, Bryan Wayne Sparks and Linus Torvalds.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] Other people on the project were Keith Bostic, Chuck Cranor, Michael Davidson, Chris G.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] Demetriou, Ulrich Drepper, Don Dugger, Steve Ginzburg, Jon "maddog" Hall, Ron Holt, Jordan Hubbard, Dave Jensen, Kean Johnston, Andrew Josey, Robert Lipe, Bela Lubkin, Tim Marsland, Greg Page, Ronald Joe Record, Tim Ruckle, Joel Silverstein, Chia-pi Tien, and Erik Troan.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] Operating systems and companies represented were BeOS, BSDI, FreeBSD, Intel, Linux, NetBSD, SCO and SunSoft.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] The project progressed and in mid-1998, SCO began developing lxrun, an open-source compatibility layer able to run Linux binaries on OpenServer, UnixWare, and Solaris.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] SCO announced official support of lxrun at LinuxWorld in March 1999.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] Sun Microsystems began officially supporting lxrun for Solaris in early 1999, and later moved to integrated support of the Linux binary format via Solaris Containers for Linux Applications.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] With the BSDs having long supported Linux binaries (through a compatibility layer) and the main x86 Unix vendors having added support for the format, the project decided that Linux ELF was the format chosen by the industry and "declare[d] itself dissolved" on July 25, 1999.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] FatELF is an ELF binary-format extension that adds fat binary capabilities.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] It is aimed for Linux and other Unix-like operating systems.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] Additionally to the CPU architecture abstraction (byte order, word size, CPU instruction set etc.), there is the potential advantage of software-platform abstraction e.g., binaries which support multiple kernel ABI versions.
[src:binary-analysis/executable-and-linkable-format] As of 2021, FatELF has not been integrated into the mainline Linux kernel.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] In computing, an **executable** is a resource that a computer can use to control its behavior.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] As with all information in computing, it is data, but distinct from data that does not imply a flow of control.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] Terms such as **executable code**, **executable file**, **executable program**, and **executable image** describe forms in which the information is represented and stored.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] A **native executable** is machine code and is directly executable at the instruction level of a CPU.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] A script is also executable although indirectly via an interpreter.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] Intermediate executable code (such as bytecode) may be interpreted or converted to native code at runtime via just-in-time compilation.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] Even though it is technically possible to write a native executable directly in machine language, it is generally not done.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] It is far more convenient to develop software as human readable source code and to automate the generation of machine code via a build toolchain.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] Today, most source code is a high-level language although it is still possible to use assembly language which is closely associated with machine code instructions.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] Many toolchains consist of a compiler that generates native code as a set of object files and a linker that generates a native executable from the object and other files.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] For assembly language, typically the translation tool is called an assembler instead of a compiler.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] Object files are typically stored in a digital container format that supports structure in the machine code – such as Executable and Linkable Format (ELF) or Portable Executable (PE), depending on the computing context.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] The format may support segregating code into sections such as .text (executable code), .data (initialized global and static variables), and .rodata (read-only data, such as constants and strings).
[src:binary-analysis/executable] For C, this is done by linking in the crt0 object, which contains the actual entry point and does setup and shutdown by calling the runtime library.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] Executable files thus may contain significant code beyond that directly generated from the source code.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] In some cases, it is desirable to omit this, for example for embedded systems.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] In C, this can be done by omitting the usual runtime, and instead explicitly specifying a linker script, which generates the entry point and handles startup and shutdown, such as calling `main` to start and returning exit status to the kernel at the end.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] To be executable, a file must conform to the system's application binary interface (ABI).
[src:binary-analysis/executable] In simple interfaces, a file is executed by loading it into memory and jumping to the start of the address space and executing from there.
[src:binary-analysis/executable] In more complicated interfaces, executable files have additional metadata, which may specify relocations to be performed when the program is loaded, or the entry point address at which to start execution.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] According to the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) specification, the PE format is also the accepted standard for executables in EFI environments.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] On Windows NT systems, it currently supports a range of instruction sets, including IA-32, x86-64 (AMD64/Intel 64), IA-64, ARM and ARM64.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Before the advent of Windows 2000, Windows NT (and by extension the PE format) also supported MIPS, Alpha, and PowerPC architectures.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Moreover, thanks to its use in Windows CE, PE has maintained compatibility with several MIPS, ARM (including Thumb), and SuperH variants.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Functionally, the PE format is similar to other platform-specific executable formats, such as the ELF format used in Linux and most Unix-like systems, and the Mach-O format found in macOS and iOS.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Microsoft first introduced the PE format with Windows NT 3.1, replacing the older 16-bit New Executable (NE) format.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Soon after, Windows 95, 98, ME, and the Win32s extension for Windows 3.1x, all adopted the PE structure.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Each PE file includes a DOS executable header, which generally displays the message "This program cannot be run in DOS mode".
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] However, this DOS section can be replaced by a fully functional DOS program, as demonstrated in the Windows 98 SE installer.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Developers can add such a program using the `/STUB` switch with Microsoft's linker, effectively creating a fat binary.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Over time, the PE format has grown with the Windows platform.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Notable extensions include the .NET PE format for managed code, PE32+ for 64-bit address space support, and a specialized version for Windows CE.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] To determine whether a PE file is intended for 32-bit or 64-bit architectures, one can examine the Machine field in the IMAGE_FILE_HEADER.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Common machine values are `0x014c` for 32-bit Intel processors and `0x8664` for x64 processors.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Additionally, the Magic field in the `IMAGE_OPTIONAL_HEADER` reveals whether addresses are 32-bit or 64-bit.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] A value of `0x10B` indicates a 32-bit (PE32) file, while `0x20B` indicates a 64-bit (PE32+) file.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] A PE file consists of several headers and sections that instruct the dynamic linker on how to map the file into memory.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] An executable image consists of several different regions, each requiring different memory protection attributes.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] To ensure proper alignment, the start of each section must align to a page boundary.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] For instance, the *.text* section, which contains program code, is typically mapped as an execute/read-only.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Conversely, the *.data* section, which holds global variables, is mapped as no-execute/read write.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] However, to conserve space, sections are not aligned on disk in this manner.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] The dynamic linker maps each section to memory individually and assigns the correct permissions based on the information in the headers.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] The *import address table* (IAT) is used as a lookup table when the application calls a function in a different module.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] The imports can be specified by ordinal or by name.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Because a compiled program cannot know the memory locations of its dependent libraries beforehand, an indirect jump is necessary for API calls.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] As the dynamic linker holds modules and resolves dependencies, it populates the IAT slots with actual addresses of the corresponding library functions.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Although this adds an extra jump, incurring a performance penalty compared to intermodular calls, it minimizes the number of memory pages that require copy-on-write changes, thus conserving memory and disk I/O.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] If a call is known to be intermodular beforehand (if indicated by a dllimport attribute), the compiler can generate optimized code with a simple indirect call opcode.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Modern operating systems use address space layout randomization (ASLR), a process that makes a PE file's in-memory layout unpredictable and therefore harder to exploit.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] During ASLR, the loader randomizes the virtual addresses where key components reside.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] This includes the executable's base, shared libraries, the heap, and the stack.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Most PE files are not position-independent because mainstream compilers emit some absolute references relative to an assumed base.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] To cope with randomized rebasing, the linker stores a .reloc table that lets the loader adjust those references at load time.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] In a .NET executable, the PE code section contains a stub that invokes the CLR virtual machine startup entry, `_CorExeMain` or `_CorDllMain` in `mscoree.dll`, much like it was in Visual Basic executables.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] `IMAGE_COR20_HEADER` strongly resembles PE's optional header, essentially playing its role for the CLR loader.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] The CLR-related data, including the root structure itself, is typically contained in the common code section, `.text`.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] It is composed of a few directories: metadata, embedded resources, strong names and a few for native-code interoperability.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Metadata directory is a set of tables that list all the distinct .NET entities in the assembly, including types, methods, fields, constants, events, as well as references between them and to other assemblies.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] The PE format is also used by ReactOS, an open-source operating system created to be binary-compatible with Windows.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Historically, it has also been used by other operating systems such as SkyOS and BeOS R3.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] However, both SkyOS and BeOS eventually moved to ELF.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] The Mono development platform, which aims to be binary compatible with the Microsoft .NET Framework, uses the same PE format as the Microsoft implementation.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] The same goes for Microsoft's own cross-platform .NET Core.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] On x86(-64) Unix-like operating systems, Windows binaries (in PE format) can be executed using Wine.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] The HX DOS Extender also uses the PE format for native DOS 32-bit binaries, and can execute some Windows binaries in DOS, thus acting like an equivalent of Wine for DOS.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] Mac OS X 10.5 has the ability to load and parse PE files, although it does not maintain binary compatibility with Windows.
[src:binary-analysis/portable-executable] UEFI and UEFI firmware use PE files, as well as the platform related ABI and calling convention (x64 ABI for typical PC devices) for applications.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] In other words, the entries of a symbol table store the information related to the entry's corresponding symbol.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] A symbol table may only exist in memory during the translation process, or it may be embedded in the output of the translation, such as in an ABI object file for later use.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] For example, it might be used during an interactive debugging session, or as a resource for formatting a diagnostic report during or after execution of a program.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] The minimum information contained in a symbol table used by a translator and intermediate representation (IR) includes the symbol's name and its location or address.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] For a compiler targeting a platform with a concept of relocatability, it will also contain relocatability attributes (absolute, relocatable, etc.) and needed relocation information for relocatable symbols.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Symbol tables for high-level programming languages may store the symbol's type: string, integer, floating-point, etc., its size, and its dimensions and its bounds.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Not all of this information is included in the output file, but may be provided for use in debugging.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] In many cases, the symbol's cross-reference information is stored with or linked to the symbol table.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Most compilers print some or all of this information in symbol table and cross-reference listings at the end of translation.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Numerous data structures are available for implementing tables.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Trees, linear lists and self-organizing lists can all be used to implement a symbol table.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] The symbol table is accessed by most phases of a compiler, beginning with lexical analysis, and continuing through optimization.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] A compiler may use one large symbol table for all symbols or use separated, or hierarchical symbol tables for different scopes.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] For example, in a scoped language such as Algol or PL/I a symbol "p" can be declared separately in several procedures, perhaps with different attributes.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] The scope of each declaration is the section of the program in which references to "p" resolve to that declaration.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Each declaration represents a unique identifier "p".
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] The symbol table must have some means of differentiating references to the different "p"s.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] As the semantic analyser and the code generator spend a large proportion of their time looking up entries in the symbol table, these stages have a critical effect on the overall speed of the compiler; the symbol table must be organised in a way such that entries can be found as quickly as possible.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] A common data structure used to implement symbol tables is the hash table.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] The time for searching in hash tables is relatively independent of the number of elements stored in the table (constant time), so it is efficient for a large number of elements.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] It also simplifies the classification of literals in a tabular format by including the classification in the calculation of the hash key.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] An object file will contain a symbol table of the identifiers it contains that are externally visible.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] During the linking of different object files, a linker will identify and resolve these symbol references.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Usually all undefined external symbols will be searched for in one or more object libraries.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] If a module is found that defines that symbol it is linked together with the first object file, and any undefined external identifiers are added to the list of identifiers to be looked up.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] This process continues until all external references have been resolved.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] It is an error if one or more remains unresolved at the end of the process.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] While reverse engineering an executable, many tools refer to the symbol table to check what addresses have been assigned to global variables and known functions.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] If the symbol table has been stripped or cleaned out before being converted into an executable, tools will find it harder to determine addresses or understand anything about the program.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] In addition, the symbol table may also contain entries generated by the compiler for intermediate expression values (e.g., the expression that casts the `i` loop variable into a `double`, and the return value of the call to function `bar()`), statement labels, and so forth.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] An example of a symbol table can be found in the SysV Application Binary Interface (ABI) specification, which mandates how symbols are to be laid out in a binary file, so that different compilers, linkers and loaders can all consistently find and work with the symbols in a compiled object.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] The SysV ABI is implemented in the GNU binutils' nm utility.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] This format uses a sorted memory address field, a "symbol type" field, and a symbol identifier (called "Name").
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] The symbol types in the SysV ABI (and nm's output) indicate the nature of each entry in the symbol table.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Each symbol type is represented by a single character.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] For example, symbol table entries representing initialized data are denoted by the character "d" and symbol table entries for functions have the symbol type "t" (because executable code is located in the *text* section of an object file).
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Additionally, the capitalization of the symbol type indicates the type of linkage: lower-case letters indicate the symbol is local and upper-case indicates external (global) linkage.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] The Python programming language includes extensive support for creating and manipulating symbol tables.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Properties that can be queried include whether a given symbol is a free variable or a bound variable, whether it is block scope or global scope, whether it is imported, and what namespace it belongs to.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Some programming languages allow the symbol table to be manipulated at run-time, so that symbols can be added at any time.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Racket is an example of such a language.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Both the LISP and the Scheme programming languages allow arbitrary, generic properties to be associated with each symbol.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] The Prolog programming language is essentially a symbol-table manipulation language; symbols are called *atoms*, and the relationships between symbols can be reasoned over.
[src:binary-analysis/symbol-table] Similarly, OpenCog provides a dynamic symbol table, called the *atomspace*, which is used for knowledge representation.
